1. Add PlantUML Maven Plugin for Development Only

To ensure that PlantUML is used only during development and not included in the production JAR, add the plugin under the <build> section with the maven-antrun-plugin or set the <scope> to provided (though plugins don’t usually require scopes).

✅ Recommended Approach: Add the Plugin in pom.xml

<build>
    <plugins>
        <plugin>
            <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
            <artifactId>maven-antrun-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>3.1.0</version>
            <executions>
                <execution>
                    <phase>generate-sources</phase>  <!-- Runs only during development -->
                    <goals>
                        <goal>run</goal>
                    </goals>
                    <configuration>
                        <tasks>
                            <java 
                                classname="net.sourceforge.plantuml.Run"
                                fork="true">
                                <classpath>
                                    <pathelement location="src/main/resources"/>
                                </classpath>
                                <arg value="-o"/>
                                <arg value="target/plantuml-diagrams"/>
                                <arg value="src/main/resources/*.puml"/>
                            </java>
                        </tasks>
                    </configuration>
                </execution>
            </executions>
        </plugin>
    </plugins>
</build>

2. Steps to Use PlantUML in Maven

Step 1: Install PlantUML Dependency (Development Only)

Since PlantUML is not needed in the final JAR, you can exclude it from the production package by adding it to the <dependencies> section with provided scope:

<dependencies>
    <dependency>
        <groupId>net.sourceforge.plantuml</groupId>
        <artifactId>plantuml</artifactId>
        <version>1.2023.7</version>
        <scope>provided</scope>  <!-- Ensures it's only for development -->
    </dependency>
</dependencies>

Step 2: Generate UML Diagrams

Run the following command to generate PlantUML diagrams:

mvn generate-sources

This will process .puml files inside src/main/resources/ and output the images in target/plantuml-diagrams/.

Step 3: Verify Output

Once the command executes, check the generated UML diagrams in:

target/plantuml-diagrams/

Step 4: Ensure It’s Not Packaged in JAR

To confirm that plantuml.jar is not included in your final JAR, use:

mvn package

Then inspect the JAR:

jar tf target/your-app.jar | grep plantuml

If nothing is found, that means PlantUML is excluded from production packaging.

⸻

✅ Why This Approach?

✔ Runs only during generate-sources phase (not affecting packaging).
✔ Keeps PlantUML separate from production code (scope: provided).
✔ Ensures UML diagrams are generated but not included in the JAR.

